  "articleSummary": "**Summary**  \nThe article is a hands‑on tutorial aimed at developers who need a quick, isolated database for local testing or legacy work. It explains how to spin up “throw‑away” instances of popular databases (PostgreSQL, MySQL, etc.) using single‑line Docker commands, emphasizing the benefits of container isolation for security, version control, and avoiding cross‑contamination of data. While the guide is framed as a practical, step‑by‑step cheat sheet, it includes a prominent historical disclaimer that the commands reflect a 2015 workflow and should not be used as production‑grade guidance; modern best practices (Compose files, pinned images, secrets, etc.) are mentioned as safer alternatives. The tone is upbeat and instructional, repeatedly using the metaphor of “throw‑away” containers to convey the idea of disposable, sandboxed environments. The intended audience is developers, DevOps engineers, or anyone inheriting a legacy codebase who needs a fast, reproducible database setup without affecting existing infrastructure.",
